The losers remain challengers.
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that election irregularities would have serious consequences within Zimbabwe and throughout all of southern Africa.
Despite the shadow of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they have received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe became victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats from Robert Mugabe's party, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is attributable to the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a result of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate, particularly in large parts of the rural areas.
Furthermore, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people in Harare and Chitungwiza alone stood in line without being able to cast their ballots.
I continue to doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from placing observers in 52% of the rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the voting, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the country.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
In our previous investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming body of evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, in which the incumbent president, Robert Mugabe, emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the Zimbabwean people and is considered illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe were deprived of their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The fight over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were courageous and determined and deserve to be recognized for this.
Maybe it's not too late for that.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
The government may want to arrest me.
I was already arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will to reclaim their rights and their power.
It is in our power to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
Political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
Should it come to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to see through to the end what we have begun together.
There are many heroes among the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voices must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky road together to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence while managing to preserve their lovability and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
You cannot simply leave these elections as they are, but you must not fall into Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change in the constitution, in the legal system—legitimate change—and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and malpractice in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always some kind of crisis somewhere because of elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to underhanded means when it is time to grant the people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I promise not to leave it.
